Ringgit Falls for 11th Day on Europe Debt Contagion; Bonds Gain

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-09-20T08:29:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-20/ringgit-falls-for-11th-day-on-europe-debt-contagion-bonds-gain.html
Malaysia’s ringgit fell for an 11th
day, its longest losing streak since a dollar peg ended in 2005
as  Europe ’s worsening debt crisis prompts investors to seek
safer bets than emerging-market assets.  Government bonds  rose.  The currency sank to this year’s low after  Standard &
Poor’s  downgraded its  credit rating  for  Italy  by one step to A,
saying government debt will peak at a higher level than
previously anticipated. Greek Finance Minister Evangelos
Venizelos is holding talks with European Union and  International
Monetary Fund  officials to secure a sixth installment of bailout
funds needed to stave off a default.  “ Risk aversion  has gone to the next level and the losses
are justified given that European officials have not been able
to reassure the markets on the default risk,” said Suresh Kumar Ramanathan, a currency strategist at CIMB Investment Bank Bhd.
in  Kuala Lumpur . “Asian assets are getting sold off in favor of
holding cash.”  The ringgit was 0.04 percent weaker at 3.1248 per dollar as
of 4:27 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. The currency has weakened 4.9 percent this month and
earlier touched 3.1425 today, the weakest level since Dec. 21.  Italy’s downgrade added to speculation Greece will fail to
qualify for another tranche of bailout funds from a 110 billion
euros ($151 billion) program approved by European officials and
the International Monetary Fund last year.  Foreign Selling  The FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI Index of local stocks has
declined 2.5 percent this month, contributing to a 7.1 percent
loss for 2011. Foreign funds cut their holdings of the nation’s
shares by $1.2 billion in August, the most since at least
October 2009, exchange data show.  Malaysia’s 10-year bonds snapped a four-day slide, driving
their yield down from a seven-week high, before a government
report tomorrow that’s forecast to show inflation eased for a
second month in August.  The yield on the 4.16 percent note due July 2021 fell one
basis point, or 0.01 percentage point, to 3.80 percent,
according to Bursa Malaysia.  Consumer prices rose 3.3 percent in August from a year
earlier, after gaining 3.4 percent in July, according to the
median forecast in a Bloomberg News survey. Prices jumped 3.5
percent in June, the most since March 2009.  To contact the reporter on this story:
